            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this decking calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is designed to be more practical than typical
                brand-specific tools. It works with any decking material
                (pressure-treated, hardwood, composite, PVC) and lets you
                control board size, spacing, waste factor, joist layout, posts,
                and concrete.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Deck area and perimeter</h3>
              <p>For a rectangular deck, the area is simply:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Imperial:</strong>
                  <code>Area (ft²) = Length (ft) × Width (ft)</code>
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Metric:</strong>
                  <code>Area (m²) = Length (m) × Width (m)</code>
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>The perimeter is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><code>Perimeter = 2 × (Length + Width)</code></p>
              </div>
              <p>
                If you choose “Custom total area”, the calculator uses your area
                directly and skips the length/width geometry.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Board coverage and board count</h3>
              <p>
                Each board covers a strip of deck equal to its
                <strong>effective width</strong> (board width plus gap) times
                its length.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Imperial:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >Effective width (in) = Board width (in) + Gap (in)</code
                  >
                </p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >Coverage per board (ft²) = [Effective width (in) ÷ 12] ×
                    Board length (ft)</code
                  >
                </p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >Boards (no waste) = Deck area (ft²) ÷ Coverage per board
                    (ft²)</code
                  >
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>Then the waste factor is applied:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <code
                    >Boards (with waste) = Boards (no waste) × (1 + Waste% ÷
                    100)</code
                  >
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Joists and beams</h3>
              <p>
                Joists are spaced at a regular on-center distance (e.g., 16 in).
                The calculator estimates how many joists you need across the
                deck width (or length, if joists run parallel to the boards):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong
                    >Imperial example (joists perpendicular to boards):</strong
                  >
                </p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >Number of joist spaces = Deck width (in) ÷ Joist spacing
                    (in)</code
                  >
                </p>
                <p>
                  <code>Number of joists ≈ Number of joist spaces + 1</code>
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Total joist length is the number of joists times the joist span
                (beam spacing plus overhang at each end).
              </p>

              <h3>4. Posts and concrete footings</h3>
              <p>
                Posts are assumed to be laid out on a grid under the deck. The
                calculator approximates:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <code
                    >Posts along length ≈ Deck length ÷ Post spacing along
                    length + 1</code
                  >
                </p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >Posts along width ≈ Deck width ÷ Post spacing across width
                    + 1</code
                  >
                </p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >Total posts = Posts along length × Posts along width</code
                  >
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>Each post has a cylindrical concrete footing:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Imperial:</strong>
                  <code
                    >Volume (ft³) = π × (Diameter (ft) ÷ 2)² × Depth (ft)</code
                  >
                </p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >Total concrete volume = Volume per footing × Number of
                    posts</code
                  >
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>5. Fasteners</h3>
              <p>Fasteners (screws or hidden clips) are estimated as:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <code
                    >Total fasteners = Boards (with waste) × Fasteners per
                    board</code
                  >
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>6. Cost estimation</h3>
              <p>
                If you enter unit prices, the calculator multiplies quantities
                by costs:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <code>Board cost = Boards (with waste) × Cost per board</code>
                </p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >Joist cost = Total joist length × Cost per linear ft</code
                  >
                </p>
                <p><code>Post cost = Number of posts × Cost per post</code></p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >Concrete cost = Concrete volume × Cost per cubic yard (or
                    m³)</code
                  >
                </p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >Fastener cost = Total fasteners × Cost per fastener</code
                  >
                </p>
                <p><code>Total material cost = Sum of all above</code></p>
              </div>

              <h2>Planning tips for a better deck design</h2>
              <h3>Choose the right board size and material</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>5/4 × 6 composite or PVC</strong> is common for
                  low-maintenance decks.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>2 × lumber</strong> (e.g., 2×6) is stiffer and may
                  allow wider joist spacing.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Always check the manufacturer’s
                  <strong>span tables</strong> for maximum joist spacing.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Set joist spacing by material</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Composite/PVC: often <strong>12 in or 16 in</strong> on
                  center.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Wood decking: often <strong>16 in or 24 in</strong> on center
                  depending on thickness.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For diagonal decking, many manufacturers require
                  <strong>tighter spacing</strong>.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Allow for waste and off-cuts</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Simple rectangular deck: <strong>5–10%</strong> waste is
                  usually enough.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Complex shapes, picture framing, stairs, or diagonal layouts:
                  <strong>10–15%</strong> is safer.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Order full boards; you can’t buy fractional boards, so always
                  round up.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Check codes and manufacturer instructions</h3>
              <p>This calculator is a planning tool only. Before building:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Verify <strong>local building codes</strong> for spans,
                  footing sizes, frost depth, and railings.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Follow
                  <strong>decking manufacturer installation guides</strong> for
                  spacing and fasteners.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Consult a
                  <strong>licensed engineer or building professional</strong>
                  for critical structures.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>How much decking do I need per square foot?</h3>
              <p>
                For a typical 5.5 in wide board with a 1/8 in gap, you need
                roughly
                <strong>2.2 linear feet of decking per square foot</strong> of
                deck area. The calculator uses your exact board width, gap, and
                length to compute this more precisely.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this work for composite, PVC, and wood decking?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. The calculator is material-agnostic. Just enter the actual
                board width, thickness, and price. For composite and PVC, be
                sure to use the manufacturer’s recommended joist spacing.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for metric decks?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Switch the unit system to <strong>Meters (metric)</strong>.
                All dimensions and outputs will convert to m, m², and m³, and
                concrete cost will switch to per cubic meter.
              </p>

              <h3>What about stairs, railings, and hardware?</h3>
              <p>
                This tool focuses on the main deck surface, joists, posts, and
                footings. For stairs, railings, and hardware (joist hangers,
                post bases, connectors), add an additional allowance or use
                dedicated calculators where available.
              </p>
            </section>
